But once the shutter snaps and the photo is taken, you can't unexpose the film to see

242
00:15:33,660 --> 00:15:35,700
what was hiding behind a tree in the background.

243
00:15:35,960 --> 00:15:36,580
No, you can't.

244
00:15:36,580 --> 00:15:38,620
The photograph is the trace.

245
00:15:38,800 --> 00:15:43,860
The living, breathing 3D world was the pre-image, and the pre-image is permanently gone.

246
00:15:44,660 --> 00:15:49,900
And no darkroom technique in the world, no digital enhancement can ever recover it.

247
00:15:50,280 --> 00:15:53,400
What is lost in the exposure is lost permanently.

248
00:15:54,300 --> 00:15:58,540
The 2D trace is the only identity that remains of that moment in time.

249
00:15:58,540 --> 00:16:03,260
But wait, I have to step in here and push back a little bit on behalf of humanity.

250
00:16:03,920 --> 00:16:04,400
Fair enough.

251
00:16:04,480 --> 00:16:04,760
Go ahead.

252
00:16:04,760 --> 00:16:08,880
Because what you were describing is mathematically elegant, sure.

253
00:16:09,640 --> 00:16:14,320
But humans absolutely obsess over our event words.

254
00:16:14,520 --> 00:16:15,380
We really do.

255
00:16:15,540 --> 00:16:22,300
We obsess over our histories, our traumas, the winding, painful journeys we took to get

256
00:16:22,300 --> 00:16:23,220
where we are today.

257
00:16:23,340 --> 00:16:28,500
I mean, the entire industry of therapy is based on reconstructing the pre-image.

258
00:16:28,700 --> 00:16:29,880
That's a very valid point.

259
00:16:29,880 --> 00:16:34,400
We constantly say things like, the journey matters more than the destination.

260
00:16:34,760 --> 00:16:39,180
Are you saying this paper mathematically proves our past doesn't matter?

261
00:16:39,440 --> 00:16:42,560
That only the final result is our identity?

262
00:16:42,560 --> 00:16:45,540
That is a very profound tension.

263
00:16:45,840 --> 00:16:50,340
And it's a crucial distinction that affliction actually addresses directly.

264
00:16:50,720 --> 00:16:53,240
It is not that the history doesn't matter.

265
00:16:54,120 --> 00:16:57,920
The history absolutely matters because it caused the trace.

266
00:16:57,920 --> 00:17:07,760
The specific sequence of traumas, joys, victories, and decisions is the actual mechanism that eliminated all the other possible versions of you.

267
00:17:07,760 --> 00:17:08,240
Right.

268
00:17:08,360 --> 00:17:10,920
It did the work of collapsing the Kripke frames.

269
00:17:11,080 --> 00:17:11,560
Exactly.

270
00:17:12,320 --> 00:17:17,980
But, and this is the strict mathematical precision speaking, the history is not the identity.

271
00:17:18,180 --> 00:17:21,120
The history causes the identity, but isn't the identity.

272
00:17:21,560 --> 00:17:22,700
Let's look at it like this.

273
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:26,080
Say there's a car crash and two witnesses see it.

274
00:17:26,600 --> 00:17:28,360
They might have totally different event words.

275
00:17:28,600 --> 00:17:28,900
Okay.

276
00:17:28,900 --> 00:17:35,180
One was looking at their phone and heard the screeching tires first, so they formulated a sonic memory.

277
00:17:35,300 --> 00:17:35,600
Right.

278
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:43,000
The other was staring straight at the intersection and saw the red car run the light, formulating a visual memory.

279
00:17:43,860 --> 00:17:50,080
Their individual, private journeys into that moment are totally divergent paths.

280
00:17:50,380 --> 00:17:53,380
They came at it from a completely different Kripke frame.

281
00:17:53,480 --> 00:17:53,900
Exactly.

282
00:17:53,900 --> 00:17:57,460
But the identity of the event itself is the trace.

283
00:17:57,460 --> 00:18:03,800
It's the invariant facts they both ultimately collapse upon, that the red car hit the blue car.

284
00:18:03,980 --> 00:18:04,300
Wow.

285
00:18:04,820 --> 00:18:05,120
Okay.

286
00:18:05,380 --> 00:18:08,700
The identity of the event isn't defined by their private sequences.

287
00:18:09,300 --> 00:18:11,760
It's defined by the endpoint they share.

288
00:18:11,920 --> 00:18:20,660
So, applying that to a person, my identity isn't the millions of individual agonizing choices I made over the last decade.

289
00:18:20,800 --> 00:18:21,040
No.

290
00:18:21,040 --> 00:18:29,060
My identity is the incredibly specific, highly constrained trace that managed to survive the popping of all those choices.

291
00:18:29,400 --> 00:18:31,820
I am simply the surviving residue.

292
00:18:32,080 --> 00:18:32,360
Yes.

293
00:18:32,700 --> 00:18:38,260
You are what remains, after all, incompatible possibilities have been excluded by your actions.

294
00:18:38,640 --> 00:18:39,480
That is...

295
00:18:39,480 --> 00:18:40,380
Wow.

296
00:18:40,380 --> 00:18:40,940
Okay.

297
00:18:40,940 --> 00:18:59,440
If we accept this somewhat terrifying premise, this radical, permanent separation between the rule we started with, the history of how we applied that rule, and the final result, the paper says we actually have to rewrite the fundamental rules of formal logic to accommodate it.

298
00:18:59,440 --> 00:18:59,920
We do.

299
00:19:00,580 --> 00:19:05,900
And Fliction does this by resurrecting and applying the work of a philosopher named Graham Priest.

300
00:19:06,200 --> 00:19:06,480
Okay.

301
00:19:06,620 --> 00:19:08,840
Priest has this tripartite distinction.

302
00:19:09,640 --> 00:19:10,780
Three levels of logic.

303
00:19:11,040 --> 00:19:14,940
And I'll be honest, the Latin threw me for a loop when I was reading the source material.

304
00:19:15,060 --> 00:19:16,680
It can be really dense, I know.

305
00:19:17,220 --> 00:19:20,440
But Priest's argument is foundational here.

306
00:19:20,440 --> 00:19:27,160
He argues that when we use the word logic, we are actually confusing three entirely different phenomena.

307
00:19:27,400 --> 00:19:27,600
Okay.

308
00:19:27,720 --> 00:19:28,600
Break them down for me.

309
00:19:28,920 --> 00:19:30,840
First, there is logica docents.

310
00:19:31,560 --> 00:19:33,140
Think of this as the formal theory.

311
00:19:33,640 --> 00:19:36,220
It is the rules written down in a logic textbook.

312
00:19:36,680 --> 00:19:40,460
It is the blueprint of what operations are theoretically allowed.

313
00:19:40,580 --> 00:19:40,760
Okay.

314
00:19:40,840 --> 00:19:42,220
So docents is the rule book.

315
00:19:42,360 --> 00:19:42,740
Got it.

316
00:19:42,860 --> 00:19:43,100
Correct.

317
00:19:43,580 --> 00:19:45,360
Second, there is logica utens.

318
00:19:45,660 --> 00:19:49,120
This is the actual, real-world practice of inference.

319
00:19:49,120 --> 00:19:51,240
Like actually playing the game.

320
00:19:51,820 --> 00:19:52,140
Exactly.

321
00:19:52,500 --> 00:19:59,520
It's the execution of those rules by a human brain or a silicon computer processor in real time.

322
00:19:59,880 --> 00:20:04,080
It is the temporal act of moving from premise to conclusion.

323
00:20:04,460 --> 00:20:06,640
So utens is the playing out of the game.

324
00:20:06,900 --> 00:20:09,140
And finally, there is logica ends.

325
00:20:09,640 --> 00:20:12,440
These are the terminal facts of validity themselves.

326
00:20:12,440 --> 00:20:20,700
The actual ontological outcome, independent of the rule book, and independent of our flawed attempts to execute it.

327
00:20:20,800 --> 00:20:20,940
Okay.

328
00:20:21,120 --> 00:20:30,820
So just to recap, we have the theoretical rules, which is docents, the actual execution, which is utens, and the final reality, which is ends.

329
00:20:31,140 --> 00:20:32,260
Perfectly summarized.

330
00:20:32,260 --> 00:20:42,760
Now, in reversible systems, like classical mathematics, where you can always map your way backward, these three distinct levels are violently conflated.

331
00:20:42,920 --> 00:20:44,240
They just mash them all together.

332
00:20:44,460 --> 00:20:46,800
They're treated as if they're the exact same thing.

333
00:20:47,020 --> 00:20:47,560
And why?

334
00:20:48,020 --> 00:20:50,840
Because you can always map one perfectly back to the other.

335
00:20:51,040 --> 00:20:51,300
Right.

336
00:20:51,440 --> 00:20:55,100
If you have the rule and the execution, you can perfectly predict the result.

337
00:20:55,460 --> 00:20:59,460
If you have the result and the rule, you can perfectly deduce the execution.

338
00:20:59,460 --> 00:21:01,920
Because classical math has a right inverse.

339
00:21:02,220 --> 00:21:03,420
The road goes both ways.

340
00:21:03,960 --> 00:21:06,560
But under sphere pops irreversible collapse.

341
00:21:07,280 --> 00:21:08,940
The road only goes one way.

342
00:21:09,640 --> 00:21:13,720
Therefore, these three levels are permanently severed from one another.

343
00:21:13,800 --> 00:21:15,580
They just split apart entirely.

344
00:21:15,840 --> 00:21:19,580
The formal calculus rules, the un-pocked bubbles, are docents.

345
00:21:20,620 --> 00:21:27,240
The actual real-time sequence of popping those bubbles, the irreversible trajectory of commitments, is utens.

346
00:21:27,240 --> 00:21:32,820
And the final invariant trace that survives the destruction is ends.

347
00:21:33,020 --> 00:21:35,440
Let's pull this out of abstract logic for a second.

348
00:21:35,580 --> 00:21:39,520
Because I think the symphony analogy from the paper makes this crystal clear.

349
00:21:39,900 --> 00:21:40,400
Go for it.

350
00:21:40,560 --> 00:21:42,700
Imagine you go to hear a symphony orchestra.

351
00:21:43,520 --> 00:21:47,060
The physical sheet music sitting on the conductor's stand.

352
00:21:47,300 --> 00:21:48,520
That is docents.

353
00:21:49,100 --> 00:21:51,720
It is a formal specification of what could happen.

354
00:21:51,720 --> 00:22:03,380
Now, the musicians actually sweating under the stage lights, playing their instruments, making irreversible microsecond choices about tempo, dynamics, and breath in real time.

355
00:22:04,020 --> 00:22:05,120
That is utens.

356
00:22:05,540 --> 00:22:07,880
It is the active trajectory of commitment.

357
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:08,440
Exactly.

358
00:22:08,440 --> 00:22:20,680
But the acoustic sound waves actually vibrating the air, traveling across the auditorium, and hitting the listener's eardrum sound waves, which can never, ever be unheard once they hit your brain.

359
00:22:21,100 --> 00:22:22,560
That is ends.

360
00:22:22,820 --> 00:22:24,740
That analogy captures it perfectly.

361
00:22:25,640 --> 00:22:33,800
Notice how the sheet music, the performance, and the acoustic wave are completely distinct physical objects.

362
00:22:33,940 --> 00:22:34,320
Right.

363
00:22:34,320 --> 00:22:38,480
A vinyl recording of the performance is not the score.

364
00:22:39,420 --> 00:22:41,360
The paper score is not the performance.

365
00:22:42,300 --> 00:22:48,020
And neither of them is identical to the acoustic event that has collapsed into the listener's memory.

366
00:22:48,440 --> 00:22:56,240
But in a reversible mathematical system, we pretend the sheet music and the sound wave are the exact same thing.

367
00:22:56,420 --> 00:22:56,920
Exactly.

368
00:22:57,420 --> 00:23:00,660
And fliction proves they are fundamentally mathematically distinct.

369
00:23:00,660 --> 00:23:06,620
So, if the path is destroyed, what does this mean for the concept of validity?

370
00:23:07,240 --> 00:23:13,360
Usually, if someone makes an argument, we say it's valid if it followed the rules correctly, step by step.

371
00:23:13,560 --> 00:23:22,080
Well, under irreversible collapse, validity can no longer be about preserving syntax or checking if someone followed the docents perfectly.

372
00:23:22,220 --> 00:23:24,680
Because the record of their steps is gone.

373
00:23:24,680 --> 00:23:25,360
Exactly.

374
00:23:26,200 --> 00:23:30,220
Validity must be relocated to what Fliction calls trace stability.

375
00:23:31,120 --> 00:23:36,920
If the inference leads to a stable trace that doesn't collapse into a contradiction, it's valid.

376
00:23:37,340 --> 00:23:42,640
The criterion of correctness is defined entirely by the survival of the outcome.

377
00:23:43,300 --> 00:23:45,760
Because the path taken to get there has been burned.

378
00:23:45,760 --> 00:23:48,600
This leads to a really wild question.

379
00:23:49,600 --> 00:23:58,320
If identity is just the terminal trace, and the history of how it got there is gone, how can any system ever refer to itself?

380
00:23:58,560 --> 00:23:59,560
Ah, yes.

381
00:23:59,660 --> 00:24:03,880
We have to rethink the ultimate computational party trick, don't we?

382
00:24:04,220 --> 00:24:04,880
The quine.

383
00:24:04,880 --> 00:24:09,560
This is arguably the most brilliant technical achievement of a monograph.

384
00:24:10,460 --> 00:24:17,700
But before we dive into quines, Fliction has to prove that computation isn't just about outputting numbers like 23.

385
00:24:18,060 --> 00:24:20,200
Right, we need a way to output actions.

386
00:24:20,580 --> 00:24:23,180
The paper introduces the concept of action tokens.

387
00:24:23,620 --> 00:24:27,780
Which I understood as a sort of resolve-then-discard mechanism, is that right?

388
00:24:27,880 --> 00:24:28,200
Yes.

389
00:24:29,240 --> 00:24:33,160
Think of a grandmaster-level chess engine calculating its next move.

390
00:24:33,160 --> 00:24:41,160
It builds a massive, sprawling decision tree of crypty-possible worlds, scoring millions of positions with numerical values.

391
00:24:41,820 --> 00:24:43,160
That massive tree is the scaffolding.

392
00:24:44,160 --> 00:24:44,600
Exactly.

393
00:24:45,240 --> 00:24:51,060
Once the calculation is completely finished, the engine doesn't print out the millions of numbers.

394
00:24:52,180 --> 00:24:57,160
The scaffolding is discarded, and what remains is a single action token.

395
00:24:58,040 --> 00:24:59,660
Move the knight to E5.

396
00:24:59,660 --> 00:25:09,540
So, the elaborate math was merely the mechanism used to collapse the massive option space down to a single, executable action.

397
00:25:09,780 --> 00:25:10,340
Precisely.

398
00:25:10,780 --> 00:25:16,120
Okay, so a program can reduce down to an action, or a state of being, not just a number.

399
00:25:16,820 --> 00:25:20,220
With that established, we can finally tackle quines.

400
00:25:20,660 --> 00:25:20,980
Yes.

401
00:25:20,980 --> 00:25:27,900
For anyone who hasn't spent time in computer science classes, a quine is a very specific type of program.

402
00:25:28,200 --> 00:25:34,240
It takes absolutely no input from the user, and its only job is to output its own source code.

403
00:25:34,360 --> 00:25:36,760
Right, the program that prints a perfect copy of itself.

404
00:25:36,940 --> 00:25:39,320
It is the classic benchmark of self-reference.

405
00:25:39,960 --> 00:25:44,520
But classical quines work by preserving their own syntactic structure, right?

406
00:25:44,640 --> 00:25:45,200
They do.

407
00:25:45,200 --> 00:25:50,420
They essentially have to hide a complex blueprint of themselves inside themselves.

408
00:25:50,680 --> 00:25:58,060
Which requires a reversible or lossless environment to carry that blueprint safely through the execution process to the final output screen.

409
00:25:58,360 --> 00:26:05,880
But we just spent the last 20 minutes establishing that in SpherePop, the environment is the exact opposite of lossless.

410
00:26:06,280 --> 00:26:09,920
In SpherePop, the pre-image is always destroyed.

411
00:26:10,900 --> 00:26:13,060
Evaluation eliminates structure.

412
00:26:13,060 --> 00:26:26,640
So if a program tries to hide a blueprint of itself inside itself, the very act of running the program will mercilessly crush and pop that blueprint along with everything else.

413
00:26:26,760 --> 00:26:27,320
Oh, man.

414
00:26:27,780 --> 00:26:33,060
So a classical quine, as we know it, is mathematically impossible in an irreversible system.

415
00:26:33,700 --> 00:26:34,100
It is.

416
00:26:34,100 --> 00:26:45,420
It's like trying to put a mirror inside an onion and hoping that after you violently chop the onion into pieces, the diced pile still perfectly reflects the image of the whole uncut onion.

417
00:26:45,800 --> 00:26:48,400
The physics of the system just won't allow it.

418
00:26:48,640 --> 00:26:50,080
That is exactly the problem.

419
00:26:50,320 --> 00:26:54,480
So fliction introduces a radical alternative, the SpherePop quine.

420
00:26:54,660 --> 00:26:55,740
Okay, how does that work?

421
00:26:55,740 --> 00:27:06,500
Instead of a program that reproduces its own source code, which we know is impossible, a SpherePop quine is an expression whose evaluation yields a trace that is equivalent to itself.

422
00:27:06,960 --> 00:27:09,800
I really need you to walk me through how that is possible.

423
00:27:10,040 --> 00:27:13,900
How does it achieve self-reference without reproducing its source code?

424
00:27:13,900 --> 00:27:16,820
The paper gives a specific instructive proof.

425
00:27:17,440 --> 00:27:27,460
I'll simplify the notation, but the quine is written essentially as Q equals A is A, where A equals SpherePop normal form.

426
00:27:27,700 --> 00:27:28,180
Whoa.

427
00:27:29,180 --> 00:27:30,940
That is incredibly meta.

428
00:27:31,120 --> 00:27:31,780
It really is.

429
00:27:32,220 --> 00:27:41,320
When you run this expression through the SpherePop production rules, all the nested bubbles begin to collapse via a process called lexical fusion.

430
00:27:41,640 --> 00:27:43,200
Okay, lexical fusion.

431
00:27:43,200 --> 00:27:46,120
The terms mutually annihilate their boundaries.

432
00:27:47,080 --> 00:27:52,020
And the final irreducible trace it spits out is the declarative statement.

433
00:27:52,900 --> 00:27:56,500
SpherePop normal form is SpherePop normal form.

434
00:27:56,680 --> 00:27:58,080
Which is literally what it is.

435
00:27:58,160 --> 00:28:00,080
It's declaring its own state of being.

436
00:28:00,240 --> 00:28:02,700
It doesn't print a text file of its code.

437
00:28:02,900 --> 00:28:03,780
It is its result.

438
00:28:03,780 --> 00:28:19,740
For this highly specific, perfectly balanced expression, the program, the docents, the execution of the program, the utents, and the final description of the program, the ends, collapse into a single, unified mathematical object.

439
00:28:19,740 --> 00:28:23,000
This totally reminds me of the retro reflector analogy.

440
00:28:23,220 --> 00:28:24,060
Yes, share that one.

441
00:28:24,340 --> 00:28:26,320
Think about a regular bathroom mirror.

442
00:28:26,860 --> 00:28:28,960
A regular mirror flips an image.

443
00:28:29,400 --> 00:28:31,780
Your left hand looks like your right hand.

444
00:28:31,920 --> 00:28:33,040
It's not a fixed point.

445
00:28:33,460 --> 00:28:35,940
The mirror fundamentally changes the input.

446
00:28:35,940 --> 00:28:52,860
But a retro reflector, like the special mirrors they left on the moon, or the safety reflectors on the back of a bicycle, uses complex internal geometry to bounce light back exactly, perfectly along the incident path it came from.

447
00:28:52,860 --> 00:28:53,660
Exactly.

448
00:28:53,920 --> 00:28:57,720
The SpherePopquine is a computational retro reflector.

449
00:28:58,520 --> 00:29:05,980
It survives the brutal, destructive collapse of evaluation by being mathematically identical to its own destruction.

450
00:29:06,260 --> 00:29:10,900
It achieves self-reference not by reconstruction, but by surviving collapse.

451
00:29:11,080 --> 00:29:19,100
The expression manages to occupy a razor-thin boundary where transformation literally becomes identity.

452
00:29:19,880 --> 00:29:21,140
It's just mind-blowing.

453
00:29:21,140 --> 00:29:27,080
But we've been talking about this in terms of abstract math, Kripke frames, and computer code.

454
00:29:27,360 --> 00:29:29,560
What about the conversation we're having right now?

455
00:29:29,780 --> 00:29:30,200
What do you mean?

456
00:29:30,600 --> 00:29:32,920
Are my words just bubbles popping in your head?

457
00:29:33,020 --> 00:29:36,500
Does this highly theoretical math actually apply to human language?

458
00:29:36,720 --> 00:29:39,980
It absolutely does, and that is where Fliction takes the paper next.

459
00:29:40,640 --> 00:29:44,900
The deep dive shifts entirely from computer science into linguistics.

460
00:29:45,040 --> 00:29:45,380
Really?

461
00:29:45,660 --> 00:29:46,040
Yes.

462
00:29:46,040 --> 00:29:53,320
Fliction derives a new grammatical framework called historical lexical functional grammar, or HLFG.

463
00:29:53,740 --> 00:29:57,960
I feel like traditional linguists are going to have a field day trying to debunk this.

464
00:29:58,020 --> 00:30:00,380
Oh, it definitely challenges the orthodoxy.

465
00:30:00,800 --> 00:30:07,280
Classical linguistics often treats a sentence as a static, well-formed architectural structure.

466
00:30:07,280 --> 00:30:09,960
Like building a bridge out of Lego bricks.

467
00:30:10,160 --> 00:30:10,580
Exactly.

468
00:30:10,840 --> 00:30:14,920
You have noun phrases and verb phrases acting as solid blocks.

469
00:30:15,520 --> 00:30:18,480
But Fliction completely discards that.

470
00:30:18,700 --> 00:30:20,880
So what replaces the Lego blocks?

471
00:30:21,160 --> 00:30:24,400
In HLFG, sentences are not static structures.

472
00:30:24,980 --> 00:30:31,760
They are temporal sequences of events that progressively, irreversibly eliminate grammatical options.

473
00:30:31,760 --> 00:30:36,080
Let's walk through the paper's example parse to see how this works in real time.

474
00:30:36,400 --> 00:30:37,320
The sentence is simple.

475
00:30:37,780 --> 00:30:39,040
The child sees the dog.

476
00:30:39,380 --> 00:30:40,720
Okay, let's look at it temporally.

477
00:30:41,240 --> 00:30:43,960
Tracking the irreversible collapse of the option space.

478
00:30:44,540 --> 00:30:45,820
You hear the first word.

479
00:30:46,360 --> 00:30:46,580
The.

480
00:30:47,080 --> 00:30:47,500
The.

481
00:30:47,800 --> 00:30:49,980
This immediately opens a bubble in your mind.

482
00:30:50,540 --> 00:30:51,580
It's a nominal scope.

483
00:30:51,980 --> 00:30:55,020
It effectively tells your brain, a noun is coming.

484
00:30:55,020 --> 00:30:58,260
So the Kripke possible worlds of the sentence just shrank.

485
00:30:58,920 --> 00:31:01,840
The next word cannot possibly be a verb like running.

486
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:02,400
Exactly.

487
00:31:02,600 --> 00:31:04,140
The option space is contracted.

488
00:31:04,360 --> 00:31:04,520
Yeah.

489
00:31:04,660 --> 00:31:06,620
Then you hear the next word, child.

490
00:31:06,940 --> 00:31:09,000
This saturates the nominal bubble.

491
00:31:09,500 --> 00:31:13,120
You now have a stable grammatical constituent.

492
00:31:13,200 --> 00:31:16,600
But the global meaning of the sentence is still wide open.

493
00:31:16,840 --> 00:31:17,220
Right.

494
00:31:17,360 --> 00:31:20,680
Because the child could be the subject performing an action.

495
00:31:20,680 --> 00:31:25,640
It could be the object receiving an action, or it could be part of a prepositional phrase.

496
00:31:26,160 --> 00:31:27,600
Then we hit the hinge of the sentence.

497
00:31:28,200 --> 00:31:28,800
The verb.

498
00:31:29,500 --> 00:31:29,980
Seize.

499
00:31:30,240 --> 00:31:30,560
Seize.

500
00:31:30,700 --> 00:31:32,780
Seize is a massive verbal commitment.

501
00:31:33,440 --> 00:31:40,380
It aggressively demands a subject which the child gracefully fulfills, and it anticipates an object.

502
00:31:40,580 --> 00:31:40,820
Okay.

503
00:31:41,080 --> 00:31:41,520
I follow.

504
00:31:41,520 --> 00:31:54,120
But crucially, the exact microsecond you process the word seize, you irreversibly eliminate all possible universes where this sentence is in the passive voice.

505
00:31:54,280 --> 00:31:54,920
Wow.

506
00:31:55,280 --> 00:31:59,560
You eliminate all Kripke frames where the child is sleeping or eating or playing.

507
00:32:00,220 --> 00:32:03,080
The option space of meaning contracts violently.

508
00:32:03,080 --> 00:32:05,260
And finally, we hear the dog.

509
00:32:05,580 --> 00:32:12,420
The second nominal bubble opens and closes instantly, satisfying the verb's demand for an object to be seen.

510
00:32:12,540 --> 00:32:14,700
And after that final word, what are you left with?

511
00:32:15,300 --> 00:32:16,440
The functional structure.

512
00:32:16,860 --> 00:32:17,820
The terminal trace.

513
00:32:18,140 --> 00:32:19,160
The logica ends.

514
00:32:19,700 --> 00:32:20,100
Yes.

515
00:32:21,080 --> 00:32:23,180
It's the logica ends of the clause.

516
00:32:23,680 --> 00:32:27,220
The final irreducible fact of who did what to whom.

517
00:32:27,220 --> 00:32:37,960
The transient acoustic scaffolding, the actual sound waves vibrating in the air, the mental parsing of the individual syllables, is consumed and discarded by your brain.

518
00:32:37,960 --> 00:32:44,060
The meaning you hold onto is just the residual trace of those irreversible grammatical commitments.

519
00:32:45,000 --> 00:32:48,400
This totally upends how we define the rules of grammar.

520
00:32:48,940 --> 00:32:54,180
Because if grammar is just the survival of traces, what exactly is a grammar mistake?

521
00:32:54,620 --> 00:32:56,180
What is ungrammaticality?

522
00:32:56,180 --> 00:33:03,260
In classical linguistics, ungrammaticality is treated as a rule violation, like breaking a law.

523
00:33:03,460 --> 00:33:05,680
But fliction redefines it entirely.

524
00:33:06,160 --> 00:33:07,960
Ungrammaticality is not a broken rule.

525
00:33:08,600 --> 00:33:10,600
It is a total collapse of the system.

526
00:33:10,860 --> 00:33:12,240
Let's take a broken sentence.

527
00:33:12,840 --> 00:33:14,140
The child see the dog.

528
00:33:14,620 --> 00:33:16,280
Singular subject, the child.

529
00:33:16,620 --> 00:33:17,780
Plural verb, see.

530
00:33:18,080 --> 00:33:18,300
Right.

531
00:33:18,300 --> 00:33:29,000
When the verb see dynamically demands a plural subject to fulfill its constraints, but the trace of the child provides a singular subject, those two constraints mutually annihilate each other.

532
00:33:29,080 --> 00:33:30,500
They just crash into each other.

533
00:33:30,500 --> 00:33:36,100
They are physically and logically incompatible within this fear-pop calculus.

534
00:33:36,780 --> 00:33:43,220
Because they cannot resolve, the option space for a valid meaning drops to zero.

535
00:33:43,940 --> 00:33:46,200
You are left with an empty trace space.

536
00:33:46,320 --> 00:33:49,200
This totally makes me think of flat pack furniture.

537
00:33:49,580 --> 00:33:50,060
Oh, go on.

538
00:33:50,060 --> 00:34:00,820
If you're building a bookshelf from Ikea, and you accidentally put a wooden panel on backward in step two, you don't actually know you've broken the rules of the bookshelf at step two.

539
00:34:01,640 --> 00:34:02,560
The piece fits.

540
00:34:02,900 --> 00:34:03,240
Right.

541
00:34:03,240 --> 00:34:11,640
It isn't until you reach step eight, when you try to attach the top shelf, and the dowel holes are facing the wrong direction and don't align with the screws.

542
00:34:12,100 --> 00:34:16,260
At step eight, the constraints mutually annihilate.

543
00:34:16,540 --> 00:34:17,940
That is so accurate.

544
00:34:18,100 --> 00:34:21,660
The option space for a working bookshelf has collapsed to zero.

545
00:34:21,860 --> 00:34:23,000
You have an empty trace.

546
00:34:23,680 --> 00:34:26,680
That is exactly what an ungrammatical sentence is.

547
00:34:26,860 --> 00:34:28,580
The sentence doesn't break a rule.

548
00:34:28,840 --> 00:34:31,880
The constraints just finally run out of options to resolve.

549
00:34:31,880 --> 00:34:37,260
That is a phenomenal analogy for how constraint satisfaction works temporally.

550
00:34:37,840 --> 00:34:43,320
And conversely, if an empty trace is ungrammaticality, what is ambiguity?

551
00:34:43,800 --> 00:34:44,560
Oh, good question.

552
00:34:44,780 --> 00:34:48,300
Flishen uses the famous linguistic example from Noam Chomsky.

553
00:34:49,160 --> 00:34:51,180
Flying planes can be dangerous.

554
00:34:51,780 --> 00:34:55,920
Does it mean the act of piloting planes is a dangerous activity?

555
00:34:56,260 --> 00:35:00,180
Or does it mean that airplanes currently in the sky are physical hazards?

556
00:35:00,180 --> 00:35:03,420
It's totally ambiguous without context.

557
00:35:03,960 --> 00:35:12,720
In HLFG, ambiguity happens when the sequence of lexical events doesn't impose enough exclusionary pressure on the system.

558
00:35:12,940 --> 00:35:15,560
Meaning the Kripke frames didn't fully collapse.

559
00:35:15,780 --> 00:35:16,440
Exactly.

560
00:35:16,840 --> 00:35:22,660
The option space shrinks as you hear the words, but it doesn't shrink all the way down to a single point.

561
00:35:23,660 --> 00:35:26,740
Multiple traces manage to survive the final collapse.

562
00:35:26,740 --> 00:35:29,640
Ambiguity isn't a failure of meaning.

563
00:35:30,080 --> 00:35:32,040
It is simply residual optionality.

564
00:35:32,520 --> 00:35:34,620
But this raises a huge red flag for me.

565
00:35:35,020 --> 00:35:39,160
What happens to the underlying logic of the universe when it hits that empty trace?

566
00:35:39,300 --> 00:35:39,720
What do you mean?

567
00:35:39,920 --> 00:35:46,860
When a flat pack furniture fails, or the sentence breaks down, or the math doesn't align, does the universe just crash?

568
00:35:46,860 --> 00:35:51,880
Because in classical logic, a contradiction isn't just a dead end.

569
00:35:52,020 --> 00:35:53,020
It is catastrophic.

570
00:35:53,640 --> 00:35:55,320
It is deeply catastrophic.

571
00:35:56,000 --> 00:36:07,980
In classical logic, a contradiction, for instance, asserting that P and not P are both simultaneously true, triggers what logicians call the principle of explosion.

572
00:36:08,640 --> 00:36:10,140
The principle of explosion.

573
00:36:10,140 --> 00:36:15,940
It sounds like something from an action movie, but it's a real mathematical hazard.

574
00:36:16,480 --> 00:36:23,940
It is a formal mathematical rule which states that if you allow even one single contradiction to exist in your logical system,

575
00:36:24,480 --> 00:36:29,120
literally every other statement in the universe can mathematically be proven true.

576
00:36:29,380 --> 00:36:30,740
Wow, that's insane.

577
00:36:30,920 --> 00:36:32,660
The system breaks by becoming infinite.

578
00:36:32,660 --> 00:36:43,340
If you accept that one equals zero, then through classical proofs, I can definitively prove that I am the Pope, the sky is made of green cheese, and water is dry.

579
00:36:43,620 --> 00:36:47,640
Because classical logic assumes you can trace everything backward and forward cleanly.

580
00:36:47,740 --> 00:36:53,860
So if the tracks are crossed by a contradiction, the mathematical train derails and just goes everywhere at once.

581
00:36:53,960 --> 00:36:54,400
Exactly.

582
00:36:54,860 --> 00:37:01,180
But in the sphere pop universe, evaluation is strictly defined as the contraction of options.

583
00:37:01,180 --> 00:37:03,220
You can never expand options.

584
00:37:03,320 --> 00:37:04,580
Okay, so what happens instead?

585
00:37:04,940 --> 00:37:15,360
So if you hit a contradiction, if constraints like our singular subject and plural verb are mutually incompatible, it doesn't trigger an explosion.

586
00:37:15,700 --> 00:37:19,320
It triggers what inflection calls null collapse.

587
00:37:19,460 --> 00:37:20,600
Null collapse.

588
00:37:20,600 --> 00:37:32,100
Because the system cannot travel backward to fix the error, and it cannot move forward through an incompatible constraint, the contradiction simply eliminates all remaining trajectories.

589
00:37:32,420 --> 00:37:33,820
The result is an infinity.

590
00:37:33,820 --> 00:37:36,360
No, the result is just the empty set.

591
00:37:37,140 --> 00:37:37,600
Null.

592
00:37:38,120 --> 00:37:42,140
And crucially, the empty trace does not entail anything else.

593
00:37:43,240 --> 00:37:51,020
Therefore, the logic of irreversible systems is what we call pair consistent, meaning it is inherently resistant to explosion.

594
00:37:51,020 --> 00:37:55,540
So classical logic is like a house built with no electrical circuit breakers.

595
00:37:55,880 --> 00:38:06,620
If one wire shores out in the kitchen toaster, the whole house catches fire, the neighborhood catches fire, and suddenly the conceptual idea of fire itself is burning down.

596
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:10,060
That's a vivid way to describe the principle of explosion, yes.

597
00:38:10,340 --> 00:38:13,440
But sphere pop logic has a built-in circuit breaker.

598
00:38:13,860 --> 00:38:17,560
A short circuit just pops the breaker, the power stops, null collapse.

599
00:38:17,820 --> 00:38:19,860
It just halts the process safely.

600
00:38:19,860 --> 00:38:22,640
That is exactly the engineering reality.

601
00:38:23,340 --> 00:38:26,060
Infliction doesn't just leave this in the realm of theory.

602
00:38:26,620 --> 00:38:36,480
The paper maps this principle directly to a real-world computer architecture called NUL convention logic, or NCL.

603
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:40,640
I've heard of this in the context of asynchronous circuit design.

604
00:38:40,840 --> 00:38:45,060
These are computer chips that don't have a master clock keeping time, right?

605
00:38:45,060 --> 00:38:52,580
Correct. Almost all modern computer chips have a clock that dictates when data moves, beating billions of times a second.

606
00:38:53,140 --> 00:38:57,020
But in NCL asynchronous chips, there is no clock.

607
00:38:57,520 --> 00:38:58,960
So how does the data move?

608
00:38:59,340 --> 00:39:01,240
Data moves organically as a wavefront.

609
00:39:01,980 --> 00:39:07,360
The logic gates only output data when all their local prerequisite conditions are fully met.

610
00:39:07,500 --> 00:39:09,000
What happens if there's an error?

611
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:15,860
If the data arriving is contradictory or incomplete, the gate doesn't panic and output garbage data.

612
00:39:16,240 --> 00:39:17,800
It simply outputs NLL.

613
00:39:18,560 --> 00:39:22,620
And the NLL state isn't just the absence of power, like turning a switch off.

614
00:39:22,780 --> 00:39:27,820
It is an active, logical value that explicitly encodes incompleteness.

615
00:39:27,820 --> 00:39:32,820
So the wavefront of data only advances when the constraints of reality are satisfied.

616
00:39:33,380 --> 00:39:33,940
Precisely.

617
00:39:34,720 --> 00:39:40,920
The empty trace in the sphere pop calculus operates exactly like the NUL state in NCL architecture.

618
00:39:42,040 --> 00:39:44,340
Contradiction doesn't propagate and explode.

619
00:39:44,820 --> 00:39:47,400
It simply terminates the local wavefront.

620
00:39:47,860 --> 00:39:52,140
This idea of wavefronts and circuits naturally scales up, doesn't it?

621
00:39:52,140 --> 00:39:55,480
Because fliction doesn't stop at computer chips and linguistics.

622
00:39:55,480 --> 00:40:01,140
If the universe operates this way at the level of logic, it must operate this way at the level of physics.

623
00:40:01,380 --> 00:40:05,500
Oh, this is where the synthesis of the monograph reaches its absolute peak.

624
00:40:05,940 --> 00:40:11,780
Let's get into the final major segment of the paper, where fliction takes this entire framework

625
00:40:11,780 --> 00:40:15,160
and drops it into actual physical category theory.

626
00:40:15,160 --> 00:40:22,440
Yes. Fliction unites the theoretical sphere pop calculus, the engineering of NUL convention logic,

627
00:40:23,000 --> 00:40:31,100
and a physical field theory known as RSVP field dynamics under one massive overarching mathematical structure.

628
00:40:31,320 --> 00:40:36,280
The paper calls this structure the category of constraint systems, or just constri.

629
00:40:36,420 --> 00:40:42,200
Yes. For context, in mathematics, category theory is essentially the mathematics of mathematics.

630
00:40:42,380 --> 00:40:43,240
The math of math.

631
00:40:43,240 --> 00:40:48,120
Okay. It is a way of looking at totally different mathematical structures

632
00:40:48,120 --> 00:40:51,420
and finding the universal translations between them.

633
00:40:52,140 --> 00:40:58,560
A category is just a collection of objects and the arrows, or morphisms, that connect them.

634
00:40:58,780 --> 00:41:00,720
And what are they in this new category?

635
00:41:01,420 --> 00:41:07,220
In the category fliction calls constri, the objects are entire state spaces of possibilities,

636
00:41:07,740 --> 00:41:10,700
and the arrows are monotone contraction operators.

637
00:41:11,200 --> 00:41:12,800
Monotone contraction operators.

638
00:41:12,800 --> 00:41:17,520
Meaning arrows that only ever point toward a smaller space.

639
00:41:17,740 --> 00:41:19,520
They only shrink the possibilities.

640
00:41:19,780 --> 00:41:21,140
They never, ever grow them.

641
00:41:21,440 --> 00:41:21,560
Right.

642
00:41:21,820 --> 00:41:28,360
And what's fascinating here is the profound implication for how we view the physical universe.

643
00:41:28,360 --> 00:41:34,300
Under this category, evolution, whether we're talking about the evolution of a math equation,

644
00:41:34,300 --> 00:41:39,740
the evolution of a spoken sentence, or the physical evolution of a thermodynamic system,

645
00:41:39,960 --> 00:41:42,540
always proceeds through monotone elimination.

646
00:41:43,040 --> 00:41:43,400
Wow.

647
00:41:43,540 --> 00:41:45,480
It is driven by an energy functional.

648
00:41:45,480 --> 00:41:49,840
But energy in this context doesn't mean heat or electricity, does it?

649
00:41:49,900 --> 00:41:51,700
It means something much more specific.

650
00:41:52,500 --> 00:41:52,780
Yes.

651
00:41:53,860 --> 00:41:58,820
Energy here represents incompatibility, or structural tension.

652
00:41:59,820 --> 00:42:04,680
When a system has high energy, it is in a state of high unresolved contradiction.

653
00:42:04,680 --> 00:42:09,880
It has a lot of Kripke worlds still violently overlapping.

654
00:42:10,100 --> 00:42:10,740
Oh, I see.

655
00:42:11,400 --> 00:42:14,500
Computation, therefore, is literally entropic descent.

656
00:42:15,240 --> 00:42:21,200
You can visualize the system as a ball rolling down a complex, multidimensional hill of energy.

657
00:42:21,200 --> 00:42:27,760
As it rolls, it is constantly eliminating incompatibilities, shedding potential,

658
00:42:28,300 --> 00:42:32,280
until it settles into a stable fixed point at the bottom of a valley.

659
00:42:32,480 --> 00:42:34,420
That fixed point is the trace.

660
00:42:34,620 --> 00:42:35,020
Exactly.

661
00:42:35,240 --> 00:42:36,980
That makes incredible visual sense.

662
00:42:37,300 --> 00:42:42,740
And the paper uses this landscape to redefine some very deep computer science concepts, too.

663
00:42:43,240 --> 00:42:43,380
Right.

664
00:42:43,380 --> 00:42:44,140
Like currying.

665
00:42:44,280 --> 00:42:47,060
Currying is named after the mathematician Haskell Curry.

666
00:42:47,380 --> 00:42:50,100
It is a technique used heavily in functional programming.

667
00:42:50,100 --> 00:42:55,020
It is the process of translating the evaluation of a function that takes multiple arguments

668
00:42:55,020 --> 00:43:00,040
into evaluating a sequence of functions, each taking a single argument.

669
00:43:00,160 --> 00:43:04,140
Like, instead of solving a complex equation f of x, y all at once,

670
00:43:04,360 --> 00:43:09,740
you solve for f of x first, which gives you a brand new, simpler function, g of y.

671
00:43:10,060 --> 00:43:10,560
Exactly.

672
00:43:11,260 --> 00:43:14,900
In classical models, functions are primitive, independent objects.

673
00:43:15,800 --> 00:43:19,380
When you curry, you are thought to be creating a brand new object.

674
00:43:19,380 --> 00:43:21,060
But under Fliction's model.

675
00:43:21,480 --> 00:43:25,900
In the Constry category, Fliction proves that currying is not creating anything new.

676
00:43:26,320 --> 00:43:31,520
It is simply fixing variables and restricting the system to a reduced energy landscape.

677
00:43:31,760 --> 00:43:32,020
Oh.

678
00:43:32,540 --> 00:43:38,420
When you lock in an input for x, you permanently slice away a massive chunk of the option space.

679
00:43:38,420 --> 00:43:42,360
The new function, g of y, isn't a new object.

680
00:43:42,880 --> 00:43:49,740
It's literally just a leftover topography of the original energy landscape that your ball is still forced to roll down.

681
00:43:50,380 --> 00:43:56,780
So, if I'm understanding this massive synthesis correctly, are you saying that mathematical calculation,

682
00:43:57,020 --> 00:44:04,360
computer logic gates, and the physical laws of entropy are literally the exact same mechanism, just wearing different hats?

683
00:44:04,360 --> 00:44:04,720
Yes.

684
00:44:04,720 --> 00:44:10,120
They are all, fundamentally, instances of the exact same underlying principle.

685
00:44:10,920 --> 00:44:14,600
Conditioning followed by minimization under irreversible descent.

686
00:44:14,680 --> 00:44:17,360
That is just staggering.

687
00:44:17,360 --> 00:44:25,300
Whether it's a theoretical bubble popping in the sphere-pop calculus, a silicon gate firing in an asynchronous NCL circuit,

688
00:44:25,620 --> 00:44:29,800
or a physical RSVP field relaxing its structural tension.

689
00:44:30,340 --> 00:44:37,480
It is all just an option space contracting toward a stable, minimal energy trace.

690
00:44:37,640 --> 00:44:43,640
It's all just the universe desperately trying to find the lowest possible point of incompatibility.

691
00:44:43,640 --> 00:44:52,940
And ambiguity, like our flying planes can be a dangerous sentence, is just when a physical system has multiple basins of attraction.

692
00:44:53,580 --> 00:44:57,280
It's an energy landscape with two distinct valleys at the bottom.

693
00:44:57,380 --> 00:44:59,260
And the ball doesn't know which one to pick.

694
00:44:59,500 --> 00:45:05,980
The rolling ball of the system could fall into either one, and it remains metastable, suspended on the ridge,

695
00:45:06,400 --> 00:45:11,620
until a final tiny constraint nudges it over the edge into one valley or the other.

696
00:45:11,620 --> 00:45:16,980
To really wrap our minds around this massive, intimidating, theoretical framework,

697
00:45:17,300 --> 00:45:21,400
I want to spend our remaining time looking at the paper's empirical signatures.

698
00:45:21,760 --> 00:45:22,440
Let's do it.

